snippet.textDisplay:
I think it's Corning that created a fibre optic cable not too long ago that was... not unbreakable, but freakishly rugged. They did a demonstration where you have a guy who's stapling the cable into a wood plank, wrapping it tight around a thin bar. Things that would usually destroy a typical fiber (or at least cause it to be bent to the point that total internal refraction is no longer possible). But somehow... the signal kept going through it just fine. It was all proprietary and secret, but it was really cool. The ends are still fragile though.


Here's the video, skip ahead to around 5:40 to see him stapling it. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UBt00CVvMBA
